Geospatial Data Analysis¶

Intro the data and project
The Bigfoot is a mythical creature described in North American folklore, said to inhabit remote jungles. It first appeared in the Humboldt Times in 1958, when journalist Andrew Genzoli filmed a giant primate footprint found next to a bulldozer and named it Bigfoot. Our project is verifying the biological characteristics of Bigfoot and try to find connection between economic (or social) indicators and sightings from the data set that assembled by the Bigfoot Field Researchers OrganizationBFRO. The data set contains 4747 records of Bigfoot sighting in the US. Besides the geospatial data, this data set also include the variables: date of sighting, classification which is a standard made by BFRO to classified the clarity of the sighting, and descriptions of location and situation of the sighting.
Methodology
Base on the data set from BFRO, we plan to conduct word cloud,bar plot for finding Bigfoot's height,Geospatial map of sightings, time series and scatter plot. We plan to use word clouds to find Bigfoot's habitat characteristics. The word cloud are extracted from the description variable that are at least five letters long. The stopwords are "english" stopwords from nltk.corpus package adding several additional words such as "would" and "could". For Bigfoot's height, we extracted the phrases about Bigfoots height 5 to 9 feet tall, such as "7 feet tall", "8' tall", from the description variable and created a bar plot showing the perceived height of Bigfoots. We use the map to help us identify where Bigfoot sightings occur frequently. Finally, we will use scatter plots to see if Bigfoot sightings correlate with county-level economic and social indicators.

Presentation of result

According to the Wordcloud of the description details in the data set, we found the most frequently appear words are woods, houses,sound, looked,trees,night and trail. Those words indicate that most of the sightings are happened in night and lack of direct sightings. Most of sightings are forest related.

According to the Wordcloud of the locations details in the data set, we found that most frequently appear words are River, Highway, and other words not that frequently appear but most of them are related to the area that humans rarely appear and inhabit.

The bar plot shows Height record in the data set. According to the plot, we believe that the height of Bigfoot is probably between 7 feet to 8 feet tall.

From 1958, the first official record of Bigfoot sightings, the sightings of bigfoot doesnt show seasonality but show upward trend. In 1967, Roger Patterson and his companion Bob Gimlin saw Bigfoot in a California valley and took a minute-long video. Although the video was later proven to be fake, it set off a Bigfoot hunting frenzy across the United States. At the same time, thanks to the popularization and development of the Internet, communication technology and imaging technology, people are more willing and more convenient to disseminate and record possible Bigfoot sightings.

According to the map, we found that Bigfoot sightings are widely distributed in the eastern and western United States, which is highly correlated with the high-frequency words fed back by wordcloud. The central United States is plain, while the east and west have extensive mountainous terrain with higher elevations. The states with the most sightings, Washington, Oregon, California and Arizona, have vast forested areas and high-altitude landforms. This is also corroborated by the results of wordcloud feedback.

By looking at the scatterplot of the number of sightings and county-level per capita income, we didnt find a very clear correlation. If we only look at counties with more than 10 sightings, we find that a large number of sightings are concentrated in the middle-income range. This may be because counties in the high-income bracket have higher-than-standard frequencies of human activity. Forests and mountains are widely distributed in counties in the middle-income range. According to the information obtained by wordcloud, the habitat of Bigfoot is more in line with the geographical characteristics of counties in the middle-income range.

From he scatterplot of the number of sightings and county-level population, we did not find a very clear correlation.We drop population > 5000000 due to they are outliers.Through the density and distribution of observation points, we can observe that counties with lower populations have more sightings, which is consistent with the characteristics of Bigfoot preferring to live in remote places obtained by wordcloud.

Conclusion
Through visual analysis of the Bigfoot data set, we found that Bigfoot sightings have the following characteristics: Bigfoot is about 5-8 feet tall, they mostly occur in mountains, jungles, and river areas, and sightings mostly occur at night. The places with high frequency of sightings are mostly in the eastern and western parts of the United States with high altitudes and extensive forest distribution. There are few direct sightings of sightings, and most of them are track discoveries.
